[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Expert Review
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### What's Done Well
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The three-layer architecture is the right shape.** Inflow forecasting (per source, per service, per unit), outflow / length-of-stay modeling (per-patient survival), census composition (Monte Carlo with overflow rules). Each layer answers a specific question and the answers compose. This is the chapter's clearest articulation of layered architectural reasoning so far and correctly mirrors the operational reality that census is a flow problem, not a level problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The flow-decomposition framing is the recipe's strongest single architectural insight.** "Treat census as one time series and you fit a model that has no awareness of the underlying dynamics ... the right framing is to forecast each flow separately and then compose them." This framing rules out an entire class of failure modes (model that learns seasonality but breaks on regime shifts in LOS or admit rate) and is correctly elevated as the central thesis.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The four inflow sub-source decomposition is operationally correct.** ED admissions (60-75% of community-hospital admissions, modeled as Poisson regression with calendar and weather features, ED arrival rate times admit rate), scheduled surgical (deterministic from the OR schedule with no-show and cancellation factors), direct admits (small Poisson with day-of-week features), transfers in (transfer center queue plus longer-horizon Poisson). Each sub-source has its own predictability characteristics correctly identified, and the recommendation to model them separately rather than as a single aggregate-admissions Poisson is operationally accurate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The survival-style framing for outflow modeling is the recipe's most important methods-level decision.** "For each currently-admitted patient, predict the probability they discharge in the next H hours, conditional on their length of stay so far, their service line, their disposition plan (if known), and dozens of other features. Sum the probabilities to get the expected discharge count. The advantage of this framing over a plain count-forecasting approach: it naturally incorporates patient-level information ... and it makes the discharge prediction a per-patient question, which is exactly what the case manager working the unit needs anyway." The patient-level approach is the operationally useful one and is correctly elevated as the default.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The discharge-order-as-the-strongest-single-feature framing is correct and operationally underrated.** "The last feature is the strongest single predictor: 'discharge order entered' raises the probability of discharge in the next 6 hours from a baseline of around 8 to 15% to typically 75 to 90%." The Honest Take's reinforcement that "a naive model that uses only this feature, with no calendar features, no service line, no LOS, and no demographics, beats a sophisticated model trained without the discharge order" is a real operational lesson and is correctly elevated.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The horizon-decision-coupling enumeration ties technical choices to operational consumers.** 1-4h ED diversion / transfer center / OR add-ons; 4-12h same-shift staffing pulls / discharge expediting / internal transfer prioritization; 12-24h next-shift staffing / OR adjustments / surge-plan activation; 24-72h tomorrow's bed plan / OR booking / transfer-in capacity commitments; 72h-7d weekly staffing / scheduled procedure planning. This is the recipe's most operationally-useful single framing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The Monte Carlo composition with overflow logic is correctly elevated as the engineering primitive.** "Sample N times from each component distribution (admissions, discharges, transfers), compose the census trajectory for each sample, take the mean and percentiles across samples. This naturally produces calibrated prediction intervals." The post-processing pass that respects overflow rules and produces a constrained joint forecast is correctly framed as necessary to avoid unit-level numbers that don't add up to a coherent hospital plan.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **DynamoDB access pattern matches the chapter pattern.** Partition key `unit_id`, sort key `forecast_for_timestamp`. This keeps all forecasts for a given unit in one partition for efficient horizon queries and is operationally correct for low-latency single-unit queries from bed-huddle dashboards and transfer-center decision support.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **"Why This Isn't Production-Ready" correctly elevates ten structural gaps.** ADT timestamp reconciliation, discharge order timing model, capacity constraints and overflow logic, service-line and DRG drift, multi-hospital health-system rollouts, operational integration as the hard part, feedback capture and continuous calibration, human-in-the-loop for surge planning, privacy considerations for narrative summaries, regulatory framing (operational versus clinical decision support), idempotency and rerun safety. Each is operationally accurate and would be a HIGH or MEDIUM finding if not surfaced; the recipe correctly elevates them as known scope-cuts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Variations section is well-scoped.** Joint multi-hospital forecasting with shared models, ED boarding hours forecasting, OR throughput coupling, real-time discharge prioritization, surge plan trigger automation. The cross-recipe links (12.1, 12.3, 12.4, 12.6, 12.7, 14.x) are operationally accurate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Finding A1: Step Functions Inference Pipeline Lacks Retry, DLQ, and Partial-Failure Semantics
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Severity:** HIGH
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Expert:** Architecture (orchestration, error handling, distributed systems, clinical-operational impact)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Location:** "AWS Step Functions for orchestration" paragraph in "Why These Services": "The forecast pipeline has multiple steps with explicit retry semantics: refresh current-state snapshot, run inflow models, run outflow model on every currently-admitted patient, run Monte Carlo composition, write forecasts. Step Functions orchestrates this with explicit retries and is auditable for HIPAA workflows." Mermaid diagram: `I -->|Errors / metrics| Z[CloudWatch Alarms + SNS DLQ]`.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Problem:** The recipe's prose claims "explicit retries" and the diagram includes an "SNS DLQ" notation, but the architecture text and pseudocode do not specify retry counts, backoff, DLQ routing, per-step failure-tolerance, or stale-forecast signaling for missed cycles. A Step Functions pipeline with five serial stages (state snapshot -> inflow models -> outflow model -> Monte Carlo composition -> DynamoDB write) running every 15-60 minutes has five independent failure points each cycle. Without explicit retry policy and DLQ routing, the failure modes are: (a) HealthLake search fails on a transient infrastructure issue or hits a quota and the snapshot step aborts; the inference cycle is lost and the bed huddle dashboard reads stale data; (b) any of three SageMaker endpoints returns a 5xx on a transient issue and the cycle is lost; (c) the Monte Carlo Lambda hits the 15-minute timeout on a large hospital with finer time grids and the entire cycle is lost; (d) the DynamoDB BatchWriteItem fails on a partial-success-then-throttle scenario and a subset of unit forecasts are written while others are not, leaving the dashboard with mixed staleness across units (an especially bad failure mode because a transfer-center decision based on a partial forecast can route a transfer-in to a unit whose forecast did not refresh); (e) the optional Bedrock narrative-summary call fails and the structured forecast is written but the narrative is missing, producing inconsistent dashboard rendering. This finding mirrors Finding A1 in the 12.3 expert review and Finding H2 in the 12.4 expert review and is the chapter-wide consolidation pattern.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Fix:** Add explicit retry, error-catch, and partial-failure semantics to each stage of the inference pipeline. Specifically:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   1. **Per-stage retry policy.** Each stage retries on `States.TaskFailed`, `Lambda.ServiceException`, `SageMaker.InternalErrorException`, `HealthLake.ThrottlingException`, and equivalent transient-failure exceptions up to 3 times with exponential backoff (initial 30s, multiplier 2.0, max 300s).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   2. **Catch-and-route on persistent failure.** After retries are exhausted, the stage catches into a fail-soft state that emits a CloudWatch metric (`pipeline_stage_failed` with stage and cycle dimensions), logs the failure with a PHI-scrubbed payload to a CloudWatch Logs group, and routes the failure record to an SQS DLQ for the on-call engineer to inspect.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   3. **Stale-forecast signaling.** When an inference cycle fails, the DynamoDB serving table receives an explicit "stale" marker for the affected units so the bed huddle dashboard, the transfer-center decision support, and the OR scheduler can render the staleness explicitly. This is a clinical-operational primitive: dashboards must show "forecast last refreshed 47 minutes ago" rather than implicitly displaying the previous cycle's data as current. The Honest Take's framing that "a forecast that quietly degrades is worse than no forecast" is the operational reason this matters.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   4. **DynamoDB-load partial-failure recovery.** The BatchWriteItem step retries on `UnprocessedItems` with bounded backoff (5 retries) and surfaces a metric on the count of unprocessed items. Items still unprocessed after retries route to the DLQ for replay, and the affected units get the "stale" marker until the replay completes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   5. **Bedrock optionality discipline.** The Bedrock narrative-summary step is an explicit optional branch in the state machine, not an inline call inside the DynamoDB-write step. A failure in Bedrock does not block the structured-forecast write; the narrative is added asynchronously when Bedrock recovers.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   6. **Alarm thresholds for clinical-operational risk.** CloudWatch alarms fire on `pipeline_stage_failed` count > 0 in any 60-minute window (page the on-call) and on consecutive-cycle-failures > 1 (escalate to the medical informatics director and to the bed-management team's pager).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   Update the architecture diagram explicitly: a DLQ box (SQS) wired from each stage's catch path, an SNS topic for the on-call alerts and a separate SNS topic for clinical-operational escalation, and the explicit "stale" record write path to DynamoDB.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Finding A2: Hospital-Specific Overflow Rules and Bed-Management Configuration Architecturally Implicit
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Severity:** HIGH
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Expert:** Architecture (data correctness, operational accuracy, configuration management)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Location:** "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" section, "Capacity constraints and overflow logic" paragraph: "Real hospitals have much richer overflow rules (telemetry overflows to step-down with a downgrade order, but only if the receiving unit has the right monitoring equipment; ortho post-ops can overflow to general surgery but not to medicine; ICU step-down overflows have to consider nursing ratios). Production overflow logic is hospital-specific and lives in a configuration file that the bed-management team owns and updates as protocols change. The pipeline reads this configuration; it does not hardcode the rules."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Problem:** The overflow-rules gap is correctly elevated as a production concern but is architecturally implicit in a way that produces silent miscalibration at deployment for any hospital whose overflow rules are non-trivial (which is every hospital). The Step 4 pseudocode `compose_census` takes `overflow_rules` as a parameter but the architecture does not specify: (a) where the overflow rules are stored (DynamoDB-backed config table, Parameter Store, S3-backed config file, or hardcoded), (b) the change-management workflow for overflow-rule updates (who approves a change, how is the change deployed, how is the change audited), (c) the validation step that catches malformed overflow rules before they reach production (e.g., a circular overflow chain that would cause the composition to loop, an overflow target that doesn't exist as a unit, an overflow rule that violates clinical-equivalence constraints), (d) the version-tracking and rollback path when a deployed overflow-rule change produces unexpected forecast behavior. For a pipeline whose composition step is the architectural primitive that turns flow forecasts into operational forecasts, the overflow-rule configuration is a first-class architectural concern, not a footnote. The downstream consequence is sharp: a hospital that opens a new joint-replacement program adds an ortho overflow path, deploys it, and discovers in week three that the path conflicts with an existing rule about telemetry overflow to step-down. The forecast has been wrong for three weeks and the bed-management team has been overriding it manually, slowly losing trust.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Fix:** Promote overflow-rule configuration from production-gaps prose to an architectural primitive. Specifically:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   1. **Versioned configuration store.** Store overflow rules in a DynamoDB-backed config table with attributes for `hospital_id`, `unit_id`, `rule_version`, `effective_from_ts`, `effective_to_ts` (NULL for current), `overflow_targets` (ordered list with priorities), `clinical_constraints` (e.g., "monitoring_equipment_required", "nursing_ratio_compatible"), `approver_id`, `approval_ts`, and `audit_trail_id`. The Monte Carlo composition Lambda reads the active rule set per cycle.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   2. **Change-management workflow.** Overflow-rule changes go through a Step Functions approval workflow: a draft is written by the bed-management team (via a small admin UI or a controlled CLI), validated by a Lambda that checks for circular chains, missing units, conflicting clinical constraints, and rule-set self-consistency, routed to an approver (medical informatics director or a designated bed-management lead), and only deployed after explicit approval. The approval is logged to the audit trail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   3. **Validation step before deployment.** The validation Lambda runs the proposed rule set against a synthetic-load harness (a sample inference cycle on the previous day's snapshot) and confirms the forecast does not exhibit pathological behavior (e.g., all admissions overflowing to a single unit, NaN forecasts, or per-unit forecasts diverging from the historical average by more than a configured threshold). The harness's output is part of the approval record.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   4. **DynamoDB serving record carries rule-version metadata.** Forecast records include a `rule_version` attribute so that downstream consumers and after-action reviews can identify which rule set produced which forecast. This is essential for forensic reconstruction when a forecast turns out to be wrong: was the rule set the cause, or was it the model?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   5. **Rollback path.** A deployed rule-set change can be rolled back by promoting a prior version to active. The rollback is logged to the audit trail and the pipeline continues with the prior rule set on the next cycle.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Finding A3: ADT Timestamp Reconciliation Pipeline Architecturally Implicit Despite Explicit Prose Elevation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Severity:** HIGH
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Expert:** Architecture (data correctness, silent-failure prevention)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Location:** "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" section, "ADT timestamp reconciliation and data quality" paragraph: "Every hospital we've worked with has subtle ADT data quality issues that have to be cleaned before the model can train cleanly. Discharge timestamps that fire when the order is entered rather than when the patient leaves. Transfer timestamps that reflect the bed assignment rather than the actual move. ADT messages that are dropped or arrive out of order. ADT events that conflict with the EHR's location field. Production systems include a continuous data quality monitoring layer that checks for distribution shifts in the ADT stream, alerts when timestamps look implausible, and reconciles ADT against secondary signals (bed-cleaning logs, telemetry-lead-attached events, EHR location updates). This work is unglamorous, never finishes, and is the difference between a forecast that matches reality and one that quietly degrades over six months."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Problem:** The ADT-timestamp-reconciliation gap is correctly elevated as a production concern but is architecturally implicit in a way that produces silent miscalibration. The recipe's "The data is mostly timestamped, but timestamps are not always trustworthy" framing in the Technology section correctly diagnoses the problem; the AWS Implementation section's Glue-ETL paragraph mentions "timestamp reconciliation across ADT and bed-cleaning logs" but does not specify the reconciliation pipeline, the secondary signals to consume, the conflict-resolution rules, the quarantine path for irreconcilable timestamps, or the data-quality monitoring layer. The recipe's own framing is that this is "the difference between a forecast that matches reality and one that quietly degrades over six months." The architecture should specify the reconciliation discipline as a first-class layer. The downstream consequence is sharp: a survival model trained on discharge timestamps that fire when the discharge order is entered (rather than when the patient actually leaves) is calibrated to a fiction, and the forecast it produces will systematically underestimate boarding hours and overestimate available beds. This is the recipe-distinct counterpart to Finding A2 in the 12.3 expert review (late-record reconciliation) and Finding A2 in the 12.4 expert review (baseline-reset event handling): all three are silent-correctness gaps where the prose elevates the concern but the architecture does not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Fix:** Promote ADT timestamp reconciliation from production-gaps prose to an architectural primitive. Specifically:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   1. **Multi-signal ingest.** In addition to the ADT stream, ingest secondary timestamp signals: bed-cleaning logs (the bed is actually empty when housekeeping marks it cleaned), telemetry-lead-attached events (the patient is actually on the unit when the leads attach), EHR location-field updates (the EHR's authoritative location captures the move), and badge-tap events at unit doors (where available). These secondary signals land in S3 alongside the ADT stream.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   2. **Reconciliation Glue ETL.** A scheduled Glue ETL job (hourly for the inference path, with a separate weekly pass for the training data build) consumes the ADT stream and the secondary signals and produces a reconciled timeline per encounter. The reconciliation rules are configured per timestamp type: discharge_ts is reconciled against the bed-cleaning log (the bed-empty time is more authoritative than the discharge-order time); transfer_ts is reconciled against the telemetry-lead-attached event on the receiving unit (the actual-on-unit time is more authoritative than the bed-assignment time); admission_ts is reconciled against the ED-departure timestamp (the actual-on-floor time is more authoritative than the admission-order time).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   3. **Conflict-resolution rules.** When the primary and secondary signals conflict by more than a configured threshold (e.g., 30 minutes), the encounter is flagged for manual review and quarantined from the training data build. The inference pipeline uses the secondary-signal time when available and falls back to the ADT time with a confidence score; the confidence score propagates through the survival model as a feature.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   4. **Data-quality monitoring layer.** A daily Lambda computes per-timestamp-type distribution statistics (mean and IQR of secondary-signal-minus-ADT lags by unit and by hour-of-day) and compares them against a rolling baseline. CloudWatch alarms fire on distribution shift exceeding a configured threshold (e.g., the median discharge-time-versus-bed-empty lag suddenly grows from 2 hours to 4 hours, indicating a discharge-process change that the model needs to know about). The alarm routes to the data-engineering and bed-management teams.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   5. **Backfill workflow.** When the reconciliation rules are updated or a data-quality issue is corrected upstream, a backfill Glue job re-reconciles the affected historical records and triggers downstream training-feature rebuild and survival-model retraining as needed. The backfill is logged with a `reconciliation_version` for audit trail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Finding A4: DynamoDB Write Idempotency and Conditional-Write Semantics Not Specified
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Severity:** MEDIUM
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Expert:** Architecture (idempotency, rerun safety, after-action review correctness)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Location:** Step 5 pseudocode `deliver_forecast`: "write batch to DynamoDB table_name with: partition_key = unit_id, sort_key = forecast_for_ts, attributes = full forecast object ... retry unprocessed items with exponential backoff."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Problem:** The pseudocode does not specify: (a) the idempotency key for BatchWriteItem retry on `UnprocessedItems` (since BatchWriteItem is not transactional, a partial-success-then-retry produces duplicates with different `generated_at_ts` if the timestamp is computed inside the Lambda); (b) whether the DynamoDB serving table has a `CURRENT` pointer per `(unit_id, forecast_for_ts)` for low-latency latest-cycle retrieval (the pseudocode writes a versioned record but does not specify the `CURRENT` upsert pattern that 12.2, 12.3, and 12.4 all adopt); (c) the at-least-once delivery contract from EventBridge that the inference pipeline trigger relies on (a pipeline that runs twice on the same cycle produces double writes if `generated_at_ts` is recomputed); (d) what happens when an ADT-reconciliation backfill (per Finding A3) overwrites a previously surfaced forecast for an already-passed forecast_for_ts; (e) whether the Monte Carlo trajectory archive S3 write is idempotent across reruns. The "Idempotency and rerun safety" paragraph in "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" mentions the concern but does not architecturally specify the contract. This finding mirrors Finding A3 in the 12.3 and 12.4 expert reviews.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Fix:** Specify the idempotency contract in Step 5:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   - The `generated_at_ts` is computed once at the pipeline-start step and propagated through the Step Functions state, not recomputed per Lambda invocation. Reruns of the same pipeline with the same `pipeline_run_id` produce the same `generated_at_ts`.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   - Add a `CURRENT#<unit_id>` sort-key value per `(unit_id, forecast_for_ts)` pair pointing to the latest-cycle forecast, with a conditional write: `ConditionExpression: attribute_not_exists(generated_at_ts) OR generated_at_ts < :new_generated_at_ts`. This pattern lets the bed huddle dashboard query `Query(unit_id = X, sort_key begins_with "CURRENT#")` for the latest forecast for every forecast_for_ts in the horizon without scanning historical revisions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   - The pipeline trigger from EventBridge uses a `pipeline_run_id` derived from the schedule's invocation ID so that at-least-once trigger delivery produces idempotent pipeline runs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   - The BatchWriteItem retry on `UnprocessedItems` is bounded (5 retries with exponential backoff) and surfaces a metric on the count of unprocessed items.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   - Backfill writes from ADT-reconciliation (per Finding A3) use a `revision` attribute and the `CURRENT` conditional write logic still applies; backfills are not allowed to overwrite a newer forecast cycle without explicit operator action.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   - The Monte Carlo trajectory archive S3 write is keyed by `(snapshot_ts, pipeline_run_id, sample_id)` so reruns overwrite cleanly.
