[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Finding A5: Drift Detection on Inflow Accuracy and Outflow Calibration Architecturally Implicit
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Severity:** MEDIUM
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Expert:** Architecture (operational discipline, model lifecycle)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Location:** "Amazon CloudWatch for monitoring" paragraph: "The most important metrics: forecast accuracy by horizon (mean absolute error and prediction-interval coverage at 4h, 24h, 72h), drift in feature distributions (LOS, admit rate, discharge timing), pipeline runtime, and operational consumption (how many times the bed huddle dashboard hit the API in the last hour). Forecast accuracy backfilled into CloudWatch metrics is the single most important operational signal because a forecast that quietly degrades is worse than no forecast."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Problem:** The recipe correctly elevates forecast accuracy backfilling as the most important operational signal, but the architecture does not specify the drift-detection-and-backfill pipeline: how forecast accuracy is computed per horizon per unit per service line, where realized outcomes are joined to predictions, how the backfill cadence interacts with inflow-model retraining (weekly) and outflow-model retraining (monthly), or how the calibration-store schema is structured to support after-action review. The Honest Take's "build the calibration and feedback infrastructure on day one, not month four" is a strong architectural insight that the architecture itself does not operationalize. This finding mirrors Finding A4 in the 12.3 and 12.4 expert reviews.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Fix:** Add a "Calibration and Drift Detection" architectural primitive: (1) a calibration store (S3-backed Parquet partitioned by date and unit, indexed by `forecast_run_id`) that captures every forecast cycle's predictions; (2) a daily Lambda that joins realized census (from the snapshot stream) against the predicted census from the calibration store and computes per-(horizon, unit, service-line) accuracy metrics (MAE, MAPE, p10/p50/p90 coverage); (3) a weekly Lambda that computes feature-distribution drift (LOS by service line, admit rate by source, discharge-order-to-discharge lag, hour-of-day discharge pattern) and emits drift-score metrics; (4) CloudWatch alarms on accuracy degradation exceeding a configured threshold per horizon (e.g., 4h-MAPE > 5% triggers a page; 24h-MAPE > 10% triggers a page) and on prediction-interval-coverage falling outside the nominal range (e.g., 80% nominal interval covering less than 70% empirically); (5) an after-action-review pipeline that aggregates accuracy metrics by hospital-event categories (surge events, IT outages, holiday weeks) so the operations team can see how the forecast performed in stress periods.
