[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Finding A6: Discharge-Order-Timing Model Architecturally Implicit Despite "Single Biggest Improvement" Framing
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Severity:** MEDIUM
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Expert:** Architecture (model accuracy, recipe-distinct primitive)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Location:** "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" section, "Discharge order timing model" paragraph: "The single biggest improvement to the forecast is a model that predicts when a discharge order will be entered, rather than just whether one has been entered. A patient with a planned discharge today whose order has not yet been written has different dynamics than the same patient at the same hour with the order already in. Production systems train a separate discharge-order-timing model on attending-rounding patterns, hospitalist workflow, and prior-day discharge patterns to predict discharge-order timing for currently-admitted patients without orders."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Problem:** The recipe's own framing is that the discharge-order-timing model is "the single biggest improvement to the forecast." The architecture does not specify the order-timing model, the feature inputs (attending-rounding patterns, hospitalist workflow, prior-day discharge patterns, time-since-admission, day-of-stay, day-of-week, planned-disposition status), the joining pattern with the existing survival model (feature input versus parallel sub-forecast), or the training cadence. This is the recipe-distinct counterpart to Finding A6 in the 12.4 expert review (medication and intervention awareness): both are about the pipeline knowing what the patient's clinical-operational context is when interpreting the forecast. The recipe correctly diagnoses the value-add but does not architecturally specify how to deliver it. A reader implementing the basic pipeline ships a survival model with a binary discharge-order feature and accepts the chapter-pattern result that discharge-order-already-in patients are forecasted accurately and discharge-order-not-yet-in patients are forecasted with high uncertainty.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Fix:** Add the discharge-order-timing model as a separate SageMaker endpoint and specify the architecture: (1) feature inputs from attending-rounding telemetry (when does each attending typically round on each unit, what is their typical order-entry latency post-rounding), hospitalist workflow signals (recent order-entry activity, pending orders for other patients, patient census per hospitalist), prior-day discharge patterns (how many of this attending's similarly-progressing patients had discharge orders entered yesterday by this hour), and patient state (LOS, day-of-stay, planned disposition, anticipated discharge date in the care plan); (2) a separate SageMaker endpoint serving the order-timing model (Cox proportional hazards or gradient-boosted survival model) that returns per-patient order-entry probability over the forecast horizon; (3) the survival model in Layer 2 takes the order-timing prediction as a feature input, replacing the binary "order already entered" with a probabilistic "order will be entered by hour H" so patients without orders get more accurate short-horizon discharge predictions; (4) a separate retraining cadence for the order-timing model (weekly for the first three months of deployment to track attending behavior shifts, then monthly).
