[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Problem:** The recipe correctly elevates the multi-hospital rollout pattern in both production-gaps and variations and accurately notes that shared models trained jointly across hospitals borrow strength on small-volume units while each hospital still has its own bed map, overflow rules, and data quality issues. The architecture as drawn assumes a single-hospital deployment and does not specify the multi-hospital data-plane pattern (hospital_id partition keys throughout S3, HealthLake, DynamoDB; per-hospital training data isolation; cross-hospital feature aggregation for shared models with appropriate de-identification or aggregation rules; per-hospital configuration for overflow rules and unit assignments). For a chapter that is increasingly likely to be implemented at the health-system level rather than at single-hospital scale, the multi-hospital architecture should be specified at least at the level of "here is how the partitioning works and here is what to be careful about when training shared models on multi-hospital data."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Fix:** Add a "Multi-Hospital Architecture Pattern" subsection (or extend the Variations section) that specifies: (1) `hospital_id` as a partition key in every S3 bucket layout, every HealthLake datastore (or a separate datastore per hospital with shared schema), every DynamoDB table, and every CloudWatch metric dimension; (2) per-hospital configuration for unit definitions, overflow rules, and unit-assignment classifiers; (3) shared-model training pattern: per-hospital training data is exported to a system-level training bucket with hospital_id preserved as a feature, the shared model takes hospital_id as an embedding feature, and the model is trained jointly across hospitals; (4) the BAA scope considerations (a system-level training pipeline reads per-hospital PHI and produces a shared model; the model artifact does not contain PHI but the training pipeline must be encrypted-and-audited end-to-end); (5) per-hospital deployment pattern: the shared model is deployed to a single SageMaker endpoint, but per-hospital inference passes the hospital_id as input, and per-hospital DynamoDB writes are isolated by partition key.
