[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Problem:** The architecture correctly enumerates five distinct ingest feeds (ADT, OR schedule, transfer queue, ED board, EHR patient state) but does not specify how each feed gets to AWS from the source system. The chapter-pattern Finding N2 from the 12.4 expert review elevated the same concern for the HealthLake ingest path; for 12.5, the concern is multiplied across five feeds with potentially distinct connectivity requirements. For an on-premises EHR + on-premises surgical-system + on-premises transfer-center + on-premises ED-system deployment (the most common community-hospital configuration), the path is typically a Direct Connect link or a VPN tunnel with on-premises HL7 listeners and API connectors writing to S3 via VPC endpoint. For a cloud-hosted EHR (e.g., Epic Cloud, Cerner / Oracle Health Cloud), the path may be PrivateLink (where the EHR vendor offers it) or HTTPS-with-mutual-TLS over public internet. The recipe does not specify any of this and a reader implementing the pipeline may default to a public-internet-with-API-key posture for one or more feeds, which is the wrong networking posture for PHI-bearing inbound streams. ED tracking boards and OR scheduling systems are particularly likely to be third-party SaaS products whose default integration is public-internet HTTPS; the recipe should explicitly elevate the connectivity posture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Fix:** Add a paragraph to the AWS Implementation: "Multi-feed ingest paths: each of the five inbound feeds (ADT, OR schedule, transfer queue, ED board, EHR patient state) requires its own connectivity posture. The recommended baseline is a Direct Connect link or VPN from the on-premises clinical systems to the AWS VPC, with on-premises HL7 v2 listeners and API connectors writing to S3 via S3 gateway endpoint or HealthLake via VPC interface endpoint. For cloud-hosted EHRs and SaaS clinical systems, use AWS PrivateLink where the vendor offers it (Epic Cloud and Cerner / Oracle Health Cloud both support PrivateLink for some deployments). Otherwise an HTTPS connection with mutual TLS or signed-JWT authentication and TLS 1.2 minimum (TLS 1.3 preferred), with the receiving Lambda or API Gateway in the VPC. Public-internet-with-API-key alone is not appropriate for PHI-bearing inbound streams. Map the connectivity-and-BAA inventory for every clinical-source vendor before the deployment kicks off; a missed BAA on a third-party ED tracking board is a regulatory exposure even when the AWS-side architecture is clean."
