[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Problem:** The cost estimate names "scaling with bed count and refresh cadence" as the variability axes but does not decompose how the cost actually scales. The dominant cost drivers are HealthLake storage (proportional to longitudinal encounter count), SageMaker inference invocations (proportional to active-patient count times refresh-cadence-per-day), Lambda Monte Carlo composition (proportional to unit count times sample count times cadence), and the optional Bedrock narrative-summary call rate. A reader scoping a 200-bed community hospital with 30-minute refresh versus a 1200-bed academic medical center with 15-minute refresh needs to know which factors drive the variance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Fix:** Add to the cost estimate: "Per-hospital cost scales primarily with three factors. Bed count drives HealthLake storage (longitudinal encounter retention) and outflow / survival model inference cost (one inference per currently-admitted patient per cycle). Refresh cadence drives all SageMaker invocation costs and Lambda composition costs linearly: a 15-minute cadence is 4x the cycle volume of a 60-minute cadence. Unit count drives the Monte Carlo composition cost (the trajectory tensor is `[n_samples, horizon_hours, n_units]`; doubling units doubles the sample storage and the post-processing time). The $400-$1,800/month range assumes a 200-500-bed hospital with 15-30 minute refresh cadence; a 1000+-bed academic medical center with 15-minute cadence and broader unit segmentation can reach $2,000-$4,500/month, with HealthLake storage and SageMaker inference as the dominant drivers."
