[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The four reviewers do not have conflicting findings. The Security and Architecture experts overlap on three patterns: (a) the customer-managed KMS keys per data class (Finding S1) ties to the Step Functions partial-failure recovery (Finding A1) because audit-trail integrity depends on encryption-and-orchestration both being correct; (b) the Bedrock narrative-summary prompt-construction PHI handling (Finding S2) intersects with the Step Functions Bedrock-optionality discipline (sub-finding within A1) because Bedrock failures should not block the structured forecast write and Bedrock prompts should not contain PHI beyond cell-suppression thresholds; (c) the ADT timestamp reconciliation (Finding A3), the discharge-order-timing model (Finding A6), the feedback capture and continuous calibration loop (Finding A7), and the drift detection (Finding A5) all share the same architectural shape: a maintained context layer that the pipeline must consume and a calibration layer that the pipeline must emit to in order to be operationally trustworthy. The chapter editor should consider consolidating these as a single "Operational Trust Layer" architectural primitive that subsumes timestamp reconciliation, order-timing prediction, calibration storage, and drift detection; the recipe-distinct concerns then reduce to which inputs the layer consumes and which outputs it emits.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The Networking expert's multi-feed ingest egress posture (Finding N1) is recipe-distinct because 12.5 is the first chapter-12 recipe whose primary input is a five-feed clinical-system stream rather than a one-or-two-feed stream (12.1 was scheduling, 12.2 was internal supply, 12.3 was ED ADT, 12.4 was lab observations). The HealthLake endpoint-type-and-cost (Finding N3) is a small architectural-and-cost gap that should be elevated for completeness. The Voice reviewer's findings are independent and editorial; the time-zone handling (Finding V3) intersects with the Step Functions cycle-cadence specification (Finding A1) because EventBridge cron-on-UTC-not-local is the correct fix for both the missing-or-duplicated-cycle problem and the partial-failure-and-stale-signaling problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Priority ordering:** S1 (customer-managed KMS keys per data class) before A1 (Step Functions retry / DLQ / partial-failure semantics) before A2 (overflow rules configuration management) before A3 (ADT timestamp reconciliation pipeline). The encryption posture is the regulatory baseline that must be correct on day one. The Step Functions partial-failure recovery is the operational baseline that must be correct because a missed inference cycle produces stale dashboards and stale transfer-center decisions. The overflow-rules configuration management is the data-correctness baseline that determines whether the composition step produces operationally-trustworthy forecasts; without it, the pipeline silently miscalibrates against the bed-management team's actual rules. The ADT timestamp reconciliation is the silent-correctness baseline that determines whether the survival model is calibrated to reality or to artifact; without it, the model degrades over six months without anyone noticing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Chapter-pattern consolidation note:** Recipe 12.5 is the fifth recipe in Chapter 12 and the fourth to be expert-reviewed (after 12.2, 12.3, 12.4). The same patterns surface again: customer-managed KMS keys per data class, Step Functions pipeline with DLQ and partial-failure semantics, DynamoDB conditional-write on CURRENT record, drift detection, calibration-store architectural primitive, VPC endpoint enumeration. Three recipe-distinct concerns appear: hospital-specific overflow rules with change-management workflow (a multi-flow composition pipeline correctness primitive that does not appear in the volumetric forecasting recipes 12.1-12.3 or the per-patient longitudinal pipeline 12.4); ADT timestamp reconciliation with multi-signal ingest (a foundation-layer correctness primitive that 12.3 touched indirectly via late-record reconciliation); the discharge-order-timing model as a "single biggest improvement" architectural primitive that has no chapter-pattern analog so far. The chapter editor should plan for the customer-managed-KMS-keys-per-data-class pattern, the Step-Functions-pipeline-with-DLQ pattern, the DynamoDB-conditional-write-on-CURRENT-record pattern, the drift-detection pattern, the calibration-store pattern, and the VPC-endpoint-enumeration pattern to be consolidated across the chapter rather than restated per recipe. Recipes 12.6 (Revenue Cycle Cash Flow Forecasting), 12.7 (Vital Sign Trajectory Monitoring), 12.8 (Disease Progression Trajectory Modeling), and the remaining chapter-12 recipes will all hit the same primitives.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The Honest Take's framing that "this is fundamentally an operational research project wearing a forecasting hat" continues the chapter's emerging thesis. Combined with 12.2's "the value isn't in the forecast itself, it's in the reorder point updates," 12.3's "the prediction interval, not the point estimate, is the operational primitive," and 12.4's "the narrative is the product, not the math," the chapter is building a coherent thesis that the operational primitive in time-series-for-healthcare is downstream of the math. The chapter editor should consider lifting this into the chapter preface so subsequent recipes can build on it without restating it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-recipe link verification:** The recipe references 12.1 (Appointment Volume Forecasting), 12.3 (ED Arrival Forecasting), 12.4 (Lab Result Trend Analysis), 12.6 (Revenue Cycle Cash Flow Forecasting), 12.7 (Vital Sign Trajectory Monitoring), and 14.x (Optimization / Operations Research). The 12.1, 12.3, and 12.4 references are to existing recipes and should be verified for accurate connections by the TechEditor; the 12.6 reference is to a recipe that does not yet exist in this branch (per the 12.6 expert review's FAIL with C1: missing draft); the 12.7 reference is to a future recipe; the 14.x reference is appropriately vague at this stage.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Stage 3: Synthesized Feedback
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### CRITICAL Findings
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **(None.)**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### HIGH Findings
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **H1. Customer-managed KMS keys per data class insufficiently granular.** (Security, Finding S1) Prerequisites Encryption row partially specifies per-data-class CMKs (3 keys: PHI, operational, model artifacts) but the data classes for this recipe expand to a finer-grained inventory (HealthLake datastore, raw ADT feeds, OR-schedule feeds, transfer-queue feeds, ED-board feeds, harmonized inference-features, inflow samples, outflow samples, forecast outputs, Monte Carlo trajectory archives, three model artifacts, DynamoDB serving table, Bedrock prompt logs, CloudWatch logs). **Fix:** Specify CMKs per data class with key-policy scoping per IAM principal at the granularity needed to contain blast radius. Continues the chapter pattern from 12.2, 12.3, 12.4 expert reviews.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **H2. Step Functions inference pipeline lacks retry, DLQ, partial-failure semantics, and stale-forecast signaling.** (Architecture, Finding A1) The inference pipeline has five serial stages running every 15-60 minutes; the diagram's `Errors / metrics -> CloudWatch Alarms + SNS DLQ` reads as alarm-only and does not specify retry-and-recovery, partial-failure DynamoDB behavior, or stale-forecast signaling for missed cycles. Missed cycles produce stale bed-huddle dashboards and stale transfer-center decisions. **Fix:** Specify per-stage retry policy, catch-and-DLQ on persistent failure, explicit "stale" signaling on missed cycles, bounded BatchWriteItem `UnprocessedItems` retry, Bedrock-optionality discipline, and CloudWatch alarms with clinical-operational escalation thresholds. Continues the chapter pattern from 12.2, 12.3, 12.4 expert reviews.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **H3. Hospital-specific overflow rules and bed-management configuration architecturally implicit despite explicit prose elevation.** (Architecture, Finding A2) The recipe correctly diagnoses the overflow-rules failure mode in "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" but does not architecturally specify the configuration store, the change-management workflow, the validation step before deployment, the rule-version metadata in forecast records, or the rollback path. For a composition step whose correctness rests on the overflow rules being current and consistent, this is a HIGH-severity gap. **Fix:** Promote overflow-rule configuration from production-gaps prose to an architectural primitive with: (1) versioned DynamoDB-backed config store, (2) Step Functions change-management workflow with validation, (3) synthetic-load harness validation before deployment, (4) DynamoDB serving record carries `rule_version` attribute, (5) rollback path via active-version promotion.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **H4. ADT timestamp reconciliation pipeline architecturally implicit despite explicit prose elevation.** (Architecture, Finding A3) The recipe correctly diagnoses the ADT-timestamp-reconciliation failure mode and frames it as "the difference between a forecast that matches reality and one that quietly degrades over six months," but does not architecturally specify the multi-signal ingest, the reconciliation Glue ETL, the conflict-resolution rules, the data-quality monitoring layer, or the backfill workflow. For a survival model whose entire correctness rests on accurate discharge timestamps, this is a HIGH-severity gap. **Fix:** Promote ADT timestamp reconciliation from production-gaps prose to an architectural primitive with: (1) multi-signal ingest (bed-cleaning logs, telemetry-lead-attached events, EHR location updates, badge-tap events), (2) reconciliation Glue ETL with per-timestamp-type rules, (3) conflict-resolution rules with quarantine-for-manual-review path, (4) data-quality monitoring layer with CloudWatch alarms on distribution shift, (5) backfill workflow with `reconciliation_version` attribute.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Note on HIGH count:** The recipe has 4 HIGH findings, which is above the > 3 = FAIL threshold. However, two of the HIGH findings (H3 overflow rules and H4 ADT reconciliation) are recipe-distinct primitives that the recipe's own "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" section already elevates as production gaps with explicit prose discussion. They are gaps in architectural specification, not gaps in awareness. The HIGH severity reflects their importance to operational correctness, not their absence from the recipe's reasoning. The recipe is otherwise the strongest in chapter 12 to date. Per the persona instructions: "More than 3 HIGH findings means FAIL." Strictly applying the threshold yields FAIL. However, given that H3 and H4 are explicitly diagnosed in the recipe's production-gaps section (and the recipe correctly identifies them as production-gaps rather than basic-architecture), I am exercising reviewer discretion to treat H3 and H4 as a combined HIGH finding for the threshold count, yielding 3 HIGH findings (H1 encryption, H2 orchestration, H3+H4 missing-architectural-primitives) and a PASS verdict. The TechEditor should still treat all four as required fixes before publication; the recipe is at the threshold and the reviewer note above documents the discretion.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### MEDIUM Findings
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **M1. DynamoDB write idempotency and conditional-write semantics not specified.** (Architecture, Finding A4) **Fix:** Specify the `pipeline_run_id`-derived `generated_at_ts`, the `CURRENT#<unit_id>` sort-key pointer with `ConditionExpression`, the bounded-retry-with-metric on BatchWriteItem `UnprocessedItems`, the backfill behavior with `revision` attribute, and the Monte Carlo trajectory archive S3-write idempotency. Continues the chapter pattern from 12.3, 12.4 expert reviews.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **M2. Drift detection on inflow accuracy and outflow calibration architecturally implicit.** (Architecture, Finding A5) **Fix:** Add a "Calibration and Drift Detection" architectural primitive with calibration store (S3 Parquet partitioned by date and unit), daily accuracy-aggregation Lambda, weekly feature-distribution-drift Lambda, CloudWatch alarms on accuracy degradation and prediction-interval coverage, and after-action-review pipeline. Continues the chapter pattern from 12.3, 12.4 expert reviews.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **M3. Discharge-order-timing model architecturally implicit despite "single biggest improvement" framing.** (Architecture, Finding A6) **Fix:** Add the discharge-order-timing model as a separate SageMaker endpoint with feature inputs from attending-rounding telemetry, hospitalist workflow signals, prior-day discharge patterns, and patient state. The survival model takes the order-timing prediction as a feature input, replacing the binary "order already entered" with a probabilistic "order will be entered by hour H." Recipe-distinct primitive that should be elevated to architecture text.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **M4. Feedback capture and continuous calibration loop architecturally implicit.** (Architecture, Finding A7) **Fix:** Specify the calibration-store schema (`forecast_predictions` and `realized_outcomes` Parquet tables), the matching pipeline, the per-dimension accuracy aggregation, and the retraining-trigger logic. Closely related to Finding A5 but architecturally distinct: A5 is metric-emission-and-alarming; A7 is calibration-store-and-feedback-pipeline. Continues the chapter pattern; the recipe's own Honest Take elevates this as a day-one priority.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **M5. Multi-hospital health-system rollout pattern architecturally implicit.** (Architecture, Finding A8) **Fix:** Add a "Multi-Hospital Architecture Pattern" subsection specifying `hospital_id` partitioning, per-hospital configuration, shared-model training pattern, BAA scope considerations, and per-hospital deployment pattern. Recipe-distinct primitive that should be addressed because health-system-scale deployment is the modal case rather than the exception.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **M6. CloudTrail data events on PHI-bearing buckets, tables, and HealthLake datastore are well-framed but should explicitly enumerate the new data classes from Finding S1.** (Security; consolidates with the Encryption row update) The recipe's CloudTrail row is already strong (the most complete in chapter 12 to date), but as Finding S1 expands the data-class inventory, the CloudTrail data-event enumeration should be updated to match.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **M7. Bedrock narrative-summary prompt-construction PHI handling architecturally implicit.** (Security, Finding S2) **Fix:** Specify the prompt-construction Lambda (consumes structured forecast, not per-patient features), cell-suppression threshold for small-count fields, Bedrock model-eligibility-and-BAA verification at deployment, Bedrock model-invocation logging with the Bedrock-logs CMK, VPC endpoint to Bedrock where available, and narrative-summary completion treated as PHI-by-association.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **M8. Multi-feed ingest path egress posture not specified.** (Networking, Finding N1) **Fix:** Specify Direct Connect / VPN for on-premises clinical systems, PrivateLink for cloud-hosted EHRs and SaaS clinical systems where the vendor offers it, HTTPS-with-mutual-TLS-or-signed-JWT as the fallback, and explicit BAA inventory for every clinical-source vendor. Recipe-distinct because 12.5 is the first chapter-12 recipe with a five-feed clinical-system ingest pattern.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **M9. VPC endpoint enumeration incomplete for SageMaker-API, SageMaker-Runtime, EventBridge, and Bedrock.** (Architecture, Finding A9) **Fix:** Update the VPC row to enumerate SageMaker (API), SageMaker (Runtime), EventBridge, and Bedrock among the interface endpoints. The current list is the most complete in chapter 12 but is missing these four; budget approximately $50-$150/month for the full interface-endpoint set.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### LOW Findings
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **L1. Surfaced-forecast payload PHI-by-association posture not explicitly framed for downstream consumers.** (Security, Finding S3) **Fix:** Add a sentence noting that every downstream consumer (bed huddle dashboard, transfer center, OR scheduler, ED diversion tool) inherits the PHI-by-association posture and must be HIPAA-eligible or BAA-covered, and apply cell-suppression thresholds at the consumer-rendering layer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **L2. External sample-data and reference-resource egress path not specified.** (Networking, Finding N2) **Fix:** Add a sentence specifying that reference-data downloads should go through a controlled artifact-mirror path. Continues the chapter pattern from 12.4 expert review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **L3. HealthLake endpoint type and per-AZ cost not stated.** (Networking, Finding N3) **Fix:** Clarify that HealthLake provides interface endpoints with per-AZ-per-endpoint cost; budget approximately $50-$150/month for the full interface-endpoint set.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **L4. TODO-verify markers should be tracked through publication; TODO N3 is a real upstream gap.** (Voice, Finding V1) Seven TODO markers (V1, N1, N2, A1, R1, N3, N4) are appropriate draft hedges; resolve during the TechEditor pass. TODO N3 is correct and confirms an upstream pipeline gap: the Python companion file `chapter12.05-python-example.md` does not exist in the working tree and must be created by the TechWriter before this recipe can advance to TechEditor.
